Food and Feeding.
Diets of South American Fur Seals change depending on season and foraging area. Lactating females are known to feed nocturnally. Prey includes vertically migrating species and mid-water and bottom-dwelling species. Around islands off Uruguay, fish is the dietary mainstay of the South American Fur Seal. Their prey includes such pelagic and demersal species such as Peruvian anchoveta (
Engraulis
ringens), weakfish (
Sciaenidae
), cutlassfish (
Trichiuridae
), and anchovy (
Engraulidae
), and cephalopods and mollusks. Sardines (
Clupeidae
), mackerel, and lobster are eaten off Chile, and squid is commonly consumed around the Falkland Islands.
